George C. Williams (1839<U+2013>1926) was a soldier in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]] who was awarded the [[Medal of Honor]].

==Biography==

Williams was born in England on December 9, 1839.<ref>[http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=1057 George C. Williams]</ref> He emigrated to the United States and joined the [[Union Army]] during the American Civil War.  He served as quartermaster sergeant of the 1st Battalion of the 14th Infantry Regiment.

He received the Medal of Honor for gallantry in action on June 27, 1862 at [[Gaines Mill, Virginia]].  The medal was issued to Williams on August 28, 1897.<ref>[http://www.qmfound.com/moh.html Quartermaster Medal of Honor Recipients]</ref>

Williams died on November 14, 1926.  He is interred at the [[Cedar Grove Cemetery (New London, Connecticut)|Cedar Grove Cemetery]] in New London, Connecticut.

==Medal of Honor citation==
While on duty with the wagon train as quartermaster sergeant he voluntarily left his place of safety in the rear, joined a company, and fought with distinguished gallantry through the action.
